                                                     All Black Sevens visit in pipeline
            A STAFF REPORTER            Armoured Corps, Ahmednagar, after winning the Main Plate All-India Rugby Championships (Division-II) at SAI Eastern Centre on Saturday. They beat Jungle Crows 37-0. Bhubaneswar RFC beat Young Rugby 56-0 to win the Losers Plate title. A Telegraph picture                           
	Calcutta: If everything goes according to plan, rugby in India is set to get a boost.         
	The International Rugby Board (IRB) feels India, currently ranked No. 84, have big potential at the international level.         
	In tune with the apex bodys interest, the Indian Rugby Football Union (IRFU) is planning to rope in New Zealands All Black Sevens side for a tour early next year.         
	IRFU development manager Greg Davey, who is on a three-year contract, said he had proposed the plan recently. Im hopeful of the New Zealand teams visit early next year. If it materialises, it will give be a tremendous boost for Indias prospects in the 2010 Commonwealth Games, Davey, a New Zealander, said.         
	Daveys target is to help India get into the top-50 before the Delhi Games.                                                                                                                       
